Future<void> populateEncylopeadicFestivals() async {
  try {
  final firestore = FirebaseFirestore.instance;
  final CollectionReference festivals = firestore.collection('Festivals');

  final List<Map<String, dynamic>> festivalList = [
    {
      "Name": "Diwali",
      "Regions": ["North", "South", "East", "West", "Central"], 
      "History": "Diwali, or Deepavali—meaning 'row of lights'—is one of India's oldest and most multi-layered festivals, with origins that predate any single mythology. The most widely known narrative traces the celebration to the return of Lord Rama to Ayodhya after 14 years of exile, having defeated Ravana and rescued Sita—the citizens of Ayodhya lit rows of oil lamps to guide him home in the darkness. In the Vaishnava tradition, it marks the day Lord Krishna defeated the demon Narakasura, freeing 16,000 imprisoned women. In the Shakta tradition, it is the night of Goddess Lakshmi's birth from the churning of the cosmic ocean. Jains celebrate it as the day Mahavira attained moksha in 527 BCE. Sikhs celebrate it as Bandi Chhor Divas—the day Guru Hargobind Singh was released from Mughal imprisonment and returned to Amritsar. The convergence of these traditions across faiths is what makes Diwali uniquely Indian: five religions, one festival of light.",
      "Significance": "Diwali operates on five distinct layers of meaning simultaneously, which is why it resonates across so many faiths and regions. At its most immediate, it is a festival of light—the physical act of lighting an oil lamp in every window is an assertion that darkness can always be overcome, one flame at a time. At its mythological layer, every tradition that celebrates Diwali—Rama's return, Krishna's victory, Lakshmi's birth, Mahavira's liberation, Guru Hargobind's release—shares the same structure: someone imprisoned or exiled returns home, and the community lights the way. At its social layer, Diwali is the great equaliser: the poorest home lights its one diya with the same intention as the wealthiest home with a thousand. At its psychological layer, the tradition of cleaning and whitewashing one's home before Diwali externalises an internal process—preparing the inner space for light. And at its philosophical layer, the Upanishadic invocation 'Tamaso ma jyotirgamaya'—lead me from darkness to light—finds its annual, physical enactment in a billion lit lamps across the subcontinent.",
      "RegionalRituals": {
        "North": "In Uttar Pradesh and Delhi, Diwali reaches its grandest form in Ayodhya, where the entire city is transformed—200,000 diyas line the banks of the Sarayu river for the 'Deepotsav,' a tradition revived in 2017 that now draws over a million visitors. In Delhi, the markets of Chandni Chowk and Karol Bagh are decorated for weeks in advance. Businessmen perform the 'Chopda Pujan' (ledger blessing) and 'Lakshmi Puja' at the precise astrological moment of 'Pradosh Kaal'—the transition between evening and night—believed to be the moment Lakshmi moves through homes that are lit and clean. Families burst firecrackers in communal open spaces, and the rooftops of every neighbourhood are lined with diyas throughout the night.",
        "South": "In Tamil Nadu, Andhra Pradesh, and Karnataka, Diwali is called Deepavali and its most distinctive feature is the pre-dawn ritual oil bath—'Ganga Snanam'—which begins before 4 AM. The household head heats sesame oil, adds specific medicinal herbs, and applies it to every family member before a bath with a paste of shikakai and turmeric. This ritual bath is believed to wash away karmic debt accumulated over the year. The family then wears new clothes—bought specifically for this morning—and bursts the first firecrackers before sunrise, because in the Southern tradition the victory of Krishna over Narakasura took place before dawn. Sweets like Mysore Pak, Soan Papdi, and Chakli are prepared at home and exchanged with neighbours.",
        "East": "In West Bengal, Diwali night belongs to Goddess Kali rather than Lakshmi—a theological divergence that makes Bengal's Diwali unique in the country. The 'Kali Puja' pandals that go up on Diwali night are as elaborate as the Durga Puja pandals of October, filled with enormous clay images of the Goddess in her most fierce form—tongue extended, garland of skulls, standing on Shiva. In Odisha, it is called 'Dipa Amavasya' and families light 'Pradeep' (traditional wicks) at the threshold and on the roof to guide the souls of ancestors who visit the earth on this night. In both states, the night is simultaneously a festival of light and a night of communion with the dead.",
        "West": "In Maharashtra and Gujarat, Diwali carries an additional New Year celebration—Gujarati New Year falls the day after Diwali (Bestu Varas), making the festival a five-day sequence of extraordinary intensity. In Gujarat, the kite-flying of Uttarayan is echoed by the decoration of buildings with thousands of earthen diyas, and the Gujarati merchant community performs 'Chopda Pujan'—the blessing of new account books and business ledgers—at the auspicious moment determined by the family's jyotishi. In Maharashtra, the 'Abhyanga Snan' (oil bath) and 'Faral'—a platter of exclusively home-made sweets and savouries like Chakli, Chivda, Karanji, and Besan Ladoo—is the centrepiece, with families spending days before Diwali in collective cooking.",
        "Central": "Celebrated with 'Govardhan Puja' and 'Gai Jagran.' In tribal areas, cattle are decorated with colors and flowers, and traditional folk dances are performed for community prosperity. In Madhya Pradesh and Chhattisgarh, Diwali blends the mainstream Hindu celebration with tribal traditions that predate the Puranic layer. In the Bastar and Surguja regions of Chhattisgarh, local deities (Devtas) are honoured alongside Lakshmi, and cattle are decorated with turmeric and brought out for 'Gai Puja' (cow worship). The 'Govardhan Puja' on the day after Diwali is observed with great seriousness—mountains of food (Anna Kuta) are offered to the deity and distributed as prasad to the entire village. In the urban centres of Indore and Bhopal, Diwali is also the largest commercial event of the year, with the bazaars of both cities drawing shoppers from across central India for weeks."
      },
