    {
      "Name": "Holi",
      "Regions": ["North", "West", "Central", "East", "South"],
      "History": "Holi is one of the oldest festivals in the Hindu calendar, with references found in texts as early as the 4th century CE in Jaimini's Purvamimamsa-Sutras. Its primary mythological root is the story of Prahlad, a devout child-prince whose father Hiranyakashipu demanded to be worshipped as God. When Prahlad refused, his aunt Holika—believed to be fireproof—tried to burn him in her lap. Prahlad emerged unharmed; Holika was consumed. The bonfire of Holika Dahan reenacts this every year, with fire symbolising the destruction of arrogance and ego. The second layer is the tradition of Braj, where Krishna—uncertain whether Radha would accept his darker skin—playfully smeared colour on her face. The Gopis of Vrindavan transformed this mischief into an annual festival of colour, joy, and the dissolution of social hierarchies. For one day, rank, caste, and grievance are buried under a coat of gulal.",
      "Significance": "Holi is the one day in the Indian calendar when the normal social order is deliberately suspended. The Holika bonfire the night before is a purification rite—the burning of old grievances, old identities, and the winter's accumulated heaviness. The morning of colour is its opposite: a return to childhood, a dissolution of hierarchy. In the Braj tradition, the theological meaning is explicit—Krishna smearing colour on Radha is an act of love that refuses the boundary between self and other; the colours spreading from person to person enact the same dissolution. The social significance is equally profound: Holi is the only occasion in traditional India when it was acceptable for a person of lower caste to throw colour on a person of higher caste, for a subject to drench a king. The festival institutionalises the momentary reversal of power as a form of social safety valve and communal renewal. Its arrival at the precise moment winter ends and spring begins adds an ecological dimension—Holi is a festival of transformation itself, the moment when the world moves from bare to full, from cold to warm, from one state to another.",
      "RegionalRituals": {
        "North": "North India is the heartland of Holi, and no place celebrates it with more intensity than Braj—the region around Mathura and Vrindavan, where the festival runs for nearly two weeks before the official Holi date. 'Lathmar Holi' at Barsana is the most famous: women of Barsana beat men from Nandgaon with wooden sticks (lathis) while the men protect themselves with shields, re-enacting Krishna's teasing of the Gopis. In Varanasi, 'Rang Bhari Ekadashi'—the day Shiva brings Parvati to Kashi—kicks off the Holi season eleven days early, with the burning ghats of Manikarnika seeing ash (vibhuti) thrown instead of colour. On Holi morning itself, the streets of every North Indian city are transformed as neighbourhoods mix in clouds of gulal that make normal social distinctions invisible.",
        "West": "In Maharashtra and Gujarat, the Holika Dahan bonfire is the most ritually significant moment of Holi. The bonfire is not lit casually—its location is determined by astrologers, the wood is of specific types, and coconuts and puffed rice are offered into the fire before it is lit. In the Pune tradition, effigies of Holika made from specific materials are carried in procession and placed in the bonfire. The morning colour play (Dhulvad) in Maharashtra has a strong folk-music dimension—traditional songs called 'Holi Fad' are sung by groups moving through neighbourhoods. In Gujarat, communities gather in large open grounds for 'Rang Utsav' events, with folk dancers performing Garba and Ras before the colour begins.",
        "East": "Bengal's version of Holi—'Dol Jatra' or 'Dol Purnima'—is one of the most elegant expressions of the festival anywhere in India. The central ritual is the 'Dol'—a flower-decorated palanquin or swing on which images of Radha and Krishna are placed and gently swung. Processions move through the streets with the Dol at the centre, accompanied by kirtan singers performing songs of the Vaishnava tradition. The colour is primarily 'abir'—a soft, dry, natural powder in deep red and pink—rather than the wet synthetic colours of the North. Rabindranath Tagore transformed Dol Jatra at Shantiniketan into a celebration of spring beauty, combining colour with classical dance, music, and the wearing of flower garlands—a tradition that continues at Visva-Bharati University every year.",
        "Central": "In Madhya Pradesh's Malwa region, Holi has an extension that is unique in India—'Rang Panchami,' the fifth day after Holi, is considered the true festival. The accumulated restraint of the first four days is released in Rang Panchami, when entire neighbourhoods empty into the streets and massive water cannons and blowers spray coloured powder and water in clouds visible from a distance. In Indore, Rang Panchami processions have been celebrated for over 200 years, with thousands of participants and the city's streets running with colour for hours. In the Gondwana tribal regions of Chhattisgarh, Holi includes traditional drum-based music and dances specific to local Gond communities, blending the Puranic festival with indigenous spring ritual.",
        "South": "In South India, Holi is less universally observed but carries a distinct mythological identity: it is 'Kamadahana'—the day Shiva burnt Kamadeva (the god of love) with a beam from his third eye after Kama dared to shoot an arrow of desire at Shiva during his meditation. The bonfire of Kamadahana is lit the night before, and in many Tamil and Kannada households, special offerings are made to Manmatha (Kama's other name) in the form of mango flowers and sandalwood paste. In modern Bengaluru and Chennai, the festival has evolved into enormous community colour events and rain dances, particularly among younger generations, blending the Braj tradition of colour with South Indian festivity."
      },     
