    {
      "Name": "Navratri",
      "Regions": ["West", "North", "South", "East", "Central"],
      "History": "Navratri—'nine nights'—is observed four times a year in the Hindu calendar, though the Sharad Navratri of autumn is the most widely celebrated. Its origins lie in the Devi Mahatmya, a text from the Markandeya Purana composed around the 5th-7th century CE, which narrates the nine-night battle between Goddess Durga and the buffalo demon Mahishasura. Mahishasura had obtained a boon making him invincible against any man or god, so the Trimurti—Brahma, Vishnu, and Shiva—channelled their combined divine energy (Shakti) into the form of a supreme goddess. For nine nights, the battle raged. On the tenth day, Durgashtami-Navami, Durga slew Mahishasura. Each of the nine nights is dedicated to a different form of the Goddess—Shailputri, Brahmacharini, Chandraghanta, Kushmanda, Skandamata, Katyayani, Kalaratri, Mahagauri, and Siddhidatri—each representing a different aspect of divine feminine power, from creation to destruction.",
      "Significance": "The significance of Navratri lies in its insistence that the highest form of divine power is feminine—a radical theological statement that has been at the heart of Indian civilisation for at least 2,500 years. The nine nights are not merely a festival calendar; they are a structured curriculum in the nine dimensions of Shakti—cosmic power—moving from the raw, protective force of Shailputri to the transcendent, wish-fulfilling grace of Siddhidatri. Each form of the Goddess addresses a specific human need and a specific obstacle: fear, desire, ignorance, ego, attachment. The Garba and Dandiya Raas dances of Gujarat—circles of dancers moving together through the night—embody the cosmological model: the Goddess at the centre, creation dancing around her. The three-day grouping within the nine nights carries additional meaning: the first three nights honour Durga (the power to destroy what must be destroyed), the middle three honour Lakshmi (the power to build and sustain), and the final three honour Saraswati (the power to know and create). The tenth day, Vijayadashami, is not the end of the festival but its culmination—the moment when inner transformation becomes outer action.",
      "RegionalRituals": {
        "West": "Gujarat's Navratri is the most exuberant expression of the festival anywhere in India and is recognised by UNESCO as Intangible Cultural Heritage. The Garba—performed in concentric circles around a lit clay pot or image of the Goddess—is not merely a dance but a complete performance tradition, with specific clapping patterns (Taali), spinning steps, and formations that vary by region and community. The Dandiya Raas—performed with decorated wooden sticks—follows Garba in the later part of the night. In Vadodara, Surat, and Ahmedabad, Navratri venues accommodate tens of thousands of dancers simultaneously, with professional musicians performing through the night. The nine nights see a different colour code each day, and the competitive dimension—with prizes for the best costume and best dancer—has made Gujarat's Navratri a pan-Indian cultural event.",
        "North": "In North India, Navratri is a period of strict Vrata (vow-keeping)—many devotees eat only specific foods (sabudana, kuttu flour, fruits) for all nine days, avoiding grains and legumes. On Ashtami (eighth day) or Navami (ninth day), 'Kanya Pujan' is performed: nine pre-pubescent girls are invited to the home, washed, their feet touched in reverence, and fed a specific meal of puri, chana, and halwa before being given gifts. Each girl represents one form of the Goddess. In the mountain regions of Himachal Pradesh and Uttarakhand, Navratri processions called 'Devi Jatras' move ancient brass images of local goddesses through the villages on decorated palanquins (Palankis), accompanied by traditional brass band music that is unique to the Pahari tradition.",
        "South": "South India's Navratri is defined by the 'Golu' (also called Bommai Kolu in Tamil Nadu and Bommala Koluvu in Andhra Pradesh)—a tiered display of dolls that fills one corner of every observant home. The shelves, built in odd numbers (5, 7, 9 tiers), display clay figurines of deities, mythological scenes, and scenes from daily life arranged with deliberate artistry. The collection is built over generations—antique dolls passed down through families sitting alongside newly acquired pieces. Women invite each other for 'Golu visits,' exchanging betel leaves, kumkum, and traditional sweets (sundal—legume-based salads, one type per day). In Karnataka, the same tradition is called 'Bombe Habba,' and in Andhra, specific scenes from the Ramayana and Mahabharata are re-enacted in miniature across the shelves.",
        "East": "In West Bengal and Odisha, the last three days of Navratri merge seamlessly into Durga Puja—the distinction between Navratri and Durga Puja is essentially non-existent in the East. The community pandals that house the Durga images are set up from the sixth day (Shashthi), and the three nights of Saptami, Ashtami, and Navami are the festival's peak. The sound of the Dhak—a large drum carried and played while walking—is the defining sensory experience of the East's Navratri, heard throughout the day and night from multiple pandals simultaneously. Sandhi Puja—the worship performed at the exact moment Ashtami transitions to Navami—is the most intense moment: 108 lamps and 108 lotus flowers are offered simultaneously.",
        "Central": "In Madhya Pradesh and Chhattisgarh, Navratri includes both the Garba-Dandiya tradition (stronger in the west of the region, influenced by Gujarat) and distinctly local traditions. The 'Jwarara' ritual—planting barley seeds in earthen pots on the first day and tending them through all nine days—is performed in most homes, with the sprouted barley measured as an indicator of agricultural abundance. In the tribal regions of Bastar (Chhattisgarh), Navratri takes a form rooted in the worship of local forest deities—the 'Devi Yatra' processions that move through village forests to honour local manifestations of the Goddess bear little resemblance to the mainstream festival but share its nine-night structure."
      },      
