    {
      "Name": "Raksha Bandhan",
      "Regions": ["North", "West", "Central", "East", "South"],
      "History": "Raksha Bandhan—'the bond of protection'—has roots that extend across multiple mythological and historical traditions. In the Bhagavata Purana, Indra's wife Sachi tied a sacred thread around his wrist before a great battle with the asuras, and he emerged victorious. In the Mahabharata, Draupadi tore a strip from her sari and tied it around Krishna's bleeding wrist; he vowed eternal protection in return. Historically, the most recorded instance is from 1535 CE: Queen Karnavati of Mewar, facing invasion by Bahadur Shah of Gujarat, sent a rakhi to the Mughal Emperor Humayun, appealing to him as a brother. Humayun, moved by the gesture, stopped his own campaign and marched to her defense—arriving too late to save her but honouring the bond. The festival as a formalised harvest ritual also has roots in the coastal communities of Maharashtra, where fishermen tie sacred threads around their wrists at the sea (Narali Purnima) as an offering to Varuna, the god of the ocean, marking the end of the monsoon and the return to the sea.",
      "Significance": "Raksha Bandhan's significance extends well beyond the sibling bond, though that bond is its emotional heart. The thread (rakhi) is technically a yantra—a sacred geometric object charged with protective intention—and the tradition of tying protective threads has roots in Vedic ritual that predate the sibling ceremony by centuries. The festival's modern form carries three simultaneous layers of meaning. The first is personal: the formalisation of protective love between siblings, a relationship that is chosen through loyalty rather than obligation. The second is social: the rakhi has historically been used to cross community boundaries—Draupadi tying a thread to Krishna, a Hindu queen sending a rakhi to a Muslim emperor—demonstrating that the bond of protection transcends religion and politics. The third is philosophical: the act of tying a thread around the wrist is a physical commitment, an embodied promise. The sister is not merely asking for protection; she is installing a reminder. The rakhi on the wrist is a constant, visible token of a relationship and a responsibility—one that, in the Hindu philosophical framework, binds the wearer as surely as any vow.",
      "RegionalRituals": {
        "North": "In North India, Raksha Bandhan is one of the year's most commercially and emotionally significant days. Sisters spend days selecting or making the perfect rakhi—ranging from a simple thread with a silver charm to elaborate creations with gemstones and embroidery. The ceremony itself is formal: the sister performs aarti (circling a flame before the brother), applies tilak to his forehead, ties the rakhi, feeds him sweets, and receives a gift in return. In cities like Delhi and Lucknow, the days before Raksha Bandhan see enormous temporary markets of rakhi sellers, and the postal system handles millions of rakhi packages sent from sisters to brothers in distant cities. The district courts and prisons of North India also have a tradition of allowing women to tie rakhis to male inmates on this day.",
        "West": "Maharashtra and the Konkan coast celebrate Raksha Bandhan as 'Narali Purnima'—Coconut Full Moon—the day the fishing communities formally mark the end of the monsoon and the beginning of the new fishing season. Fishermen offer coconuts to the sea (Varuna, the sea god) as a prayer for a safe and bountiful season. Coconuts are also distributed as prasad and eaten at home. New fishing boats are sometimes inaugurated on this day. The sibling rakhi ceremony is observed in homes alongside these maritime rituals, making Maharashtra's Narali Purnima a festival that integrates the cosmic (sibling bond, lunar calendar), the ecological (end of monsoon), and the economic (start of fishing season).",
        "Central": "In Madhya Pradesh and Chhattisgarh, Raksha Bandhan is observed as 'Kajari Purnima'—a harvest-related festival where women worship the earth and newly planted crops. The 'Kajari' folk songs of the monsoon season reach their peak on this day: women sing of the rains, the crops, the absent husbands who are away working, and the hope for a bountiful harvest. The sibling ceremony occurs within this agricultural framing—brothers and sisters in farming families often exchange the rakhi in the fields near the newly planted crop, blessing both the relationship and the harvest simultaneously. In tribal communities, the 'Kajari' singing continues through the night in communal gatherings under the full moon.",
        "East": "In West Bengal and the East, the full moon of Shravan is 'Jhulan Purnima'—the final day of the five-day Jhulan Yatra festival of Radha and Krishna. The festival centres on the image of Radha and Krishna seated on an elaborately decorated swing (Jhulan) in the temple, which devotees gently push while singing the Jhulan kirtan. The sibling rakhi ceremony exists alongside this but does not dominate. In Odisha, the same day is 'Gamha Purnima' and 'Rakhi Purnima'—cattle are bathed and decorated, and young men engage in traditional wrestling (Bahakhai) before the sibling rakhi exchange.",
        "South": "In South India, Raksha Bandhan coincides with 'Avani Avittam'—the annual renewal of the sacred thread (Yajnopavitam) worn by Brahmin men. On this Shravan Purnima, Brahmin men take a ritual bath, offer water to their ancestors, and change their sacred thread with a formal resolve to study the Vedas. The old thread is removed after a confession of the failures of the past year, and the new thread is worn with a fresh vow. In coastal Tamil Nadu and Kerala, it is simultaneously 'Upakarma'—the beginning of the traditional Vedic study season. The sibling rakhi ceremony, while practiced in the South, is a secondary observance; the primary ritual significance of the day belongs to the thread ceremony."
