    {
      "Name": "Eid-ul-Fitr",
      "Regions": ["North", "West", "Central", "South", "East"], 
      "History": "Eid-ul-Fitr—'the Festival of Breaking the Fast'—was established by the Prophet Muhammad in 624 CE in Medina, in the second year of the Hijri calendar, making it one of the two canonical festivals of Islam. The Prophet declared that the days of Eid replaced two pre-Islamic festivals of Medina that involved idle play, instituting instead a day of communal prayer, charity, and gratitude. The festival marks the completion of Ramadan—a month of fasting, prayer, and Quranic recitation commemorating the revelation of the Quran to the Prophet. The first act of Eid is the payment of Zakat-ul-Fitr, a mandatory charity given before the Eid prayer, ensuring that every person in the community can celebrate. The Eid prayer (Salat-ul-Eid) is prayed in congregation and is not held in a mosque—historically it was performed in an open field to accommodate the maximum number of worshippers. In India, the tradition of Eid has been woven into the cultural fabric since the Delhi Sultanate period, with Mughal emperors hosting public Eid celebrations at the Red Fort that were attended by people of all faiths.",
      "Significance": "The significance of Eid-ul-Fitr is rooted in the Islamic understanding of Ramadan as a complete transformation of the self—and Eid as its public celebration. A month of fasting from before dawn to sunset is not merely abstinence from food; Islamic teaching holds that the fast must extend to the tongue (no falsehood or harsh speech), to the eyes (no looking at what is forbidden), and to the hands (no wrongful action). Ramadan is intended to produce a purified self. Eid is the community's collective announcement that this transformation has been achieved—or sincerely attempted. The first act of Eid is Zakat-ul-Fitr: a mandatory donation of food or its monetary equivalent, given before the Eid prayer, ensuring that every person in the community—including the poorest—has enough to celebrate. This sequencing is deliberate: charity before celebration. The Eid prayer in an open field, with rows of worshippers of every background standing shoulder to shoulder, enacts the egalitarianism at the heart of Islamic theology—that before God, there is no rank. In India, Eid-ul-Fitr has historically been a festival of communal celebration that crosses religious lines, with Hindu and Sikh neighbours sharing in the feasting as a mark of neighbourly solidarity.",
      "RegionalRituals": {
        "North": "In Delhi, Uttar Pradesh, and the North, Eid-ul-Fitr begins before dawn with the final Sehri (pre-fast meal) of Ramadan, followed by the Fajr prayer, and then a morning of preparation—bathing, wearing new clothes, applying attar (perfume), and giving the Zakat-ul-Fitr donation before the Eid prayer. The Eid namaz at historic Eidgahs like Delhi's Jama Masjid draws tens of thousands, with worshippers spilling into surrounding streets. After prayers, the day is spent in family visits—'Eid Milan' gatherings—and the sharing of Sewaiyan (sweet vermicelli cooked in milk), Sheer Khurma, and Shahi Tukda. In Lucknow, the Eid culture is interwoven with the Nawabi tradition: the city's Eid celebration retains an elegance of dress, cuisine, and greeting etiquette that reflects its Mughal and Nawabi heritage.",
        "West": "In Mumbai, the most visible Eid celebration centres on Mohammad Ali Road in the old city—a food street that operates through Ramadan's nights and reaches its peak on Eid eve and Eid day. Phirni in clay cups, Mutton Dum Biryani, Seekh Kebabs, and Malpua are consumed in enormous quantities. The Minara Masjid area draws enormous Eid congregations. In Gujarat's Surat—historically a major trading city with a large and diverse Muslim population—Eid is a cross-community celebration, with Hindu neighbours invited to share the Eid feast in a tradition of mutual hospitality that has existed for centuries.",
        "Central": "In Bhopal—once the capital of a Muslim Princely State and still home to one of India's largest Muslim populations in a non-metro city—Eid-ul-Fitr retains a grandeur connected to its Nawabi past. The Taj-ul-Masajid ('Crown of Mosques'), one of the largest mosques in Asia, draws its largest annual congregation on Eid morning. The Bhopal Eid feast traditionally includes 'Bhopali Gosht Korma'—a slow-cooked mutton preparation unique to the city—shared with neighbours of all faiths in a tradition that local communities describe as the defining expression of Bhopal's composite culture.",
        "South": "In Hyderabad, Eid-ul-Fitr is inseparable from the city's food culture—Hyderabadi Haleem, available throughout Ramadan, reaches its peak production and consumption on Eid day. The Charminar area of the old city is brilliantly illuminated through Ramadan's last nights, and on Eid morning, the Mecca Masjid—one of the largest mosques in India, built by Muhammad Qutb Shah in 1617—holds one of the largest Eid congregations in the country. In Kerala's Malabar region, the Mappila Muslim community celebrates with 'Oppana'—a traditional song-and-clap performance by women, originally performed at weddings, that has become part of Eid celebrations. The Malabar Eid biryani (cooked in the Malabar style with short-grain rice, fried onions, and specific spice ratios) is the centrepiece of the day's feast.",
        "East": "Focuses on 'Lachha Sewaiyan' and grand prayers at Kolkata's Red Road, followed by family visits to share ancestral stories. In Bengal and the East, Eid is celebrated with the making of 'Shemai'—fine vermicelli cooked with milk and sugar—in enormous quantities, often prepared days in advance in community kitchens. The family mosque visit for Eid prayers is followed by a day of structured visiting: in Bengali Muslim tradition, the sequence of visits (from eldest relatives to youngest) is observed formally, with each host having prepared specific sweets and savouries. The Bengali Muslim literary tradition has contributed significantly to the cultural richness of Eastern Eid—poetry in the Mushaira tradition and performances of Baul music adapted for Eid contexts are features of some communities."
      },
