    {
      "Name": "Onam",
      "Regions": ["South"],
      "History": "Onam is the state festival of Kerala and one of the most elaborate harvest celebrations in India, observed over ten days in the Malayalam month of Chingam (August-September). Its central myth is the story of King Mahabali—a benevolent asura king who ruled Kerala in a golden age of perfect equality, where there was no poverty, no discrimination, and no untruth. His reign was so prosperous and his people so content that the gods grew envious and petitioned Vishnu to intervene. Vishnu took the form of the dwarf Vamana and approached Mahabali with a request: give me as much land as I can cover in three steps. Mahabali agreed. Vamana expanded to cosmic size and covered the earth and sky in two steps. For the third, Mahabali offered his own head. Vishnu pushed him into the netherworld—but, moved by his nobility, granted him the boon to return to visit his beloved people once a year. Onam is that annual homecoming. The ten-day celebration—with its Pookalam (flower carpet), Vallam Kali (snake boat races), Onam Sadya (26-dish feast on banana leaf), and Pulikali (tiger dance)—is Kerala's collective tribute to a king they still mourn and celebrate.",
      "Significance": "The significance of Onam lies in what it chooses to remember and how it chooses to remember it. Mahabali is a defeated king—pushed into the underworld by Vishnu himself. By every conventional logic of mythology, his story should be a cautionary tale. Instead, Kerala made him into their greatest hero, and the festival that celebrates his annual return is the state's most beloved. The message is explicit: good governance, justice, and the welfare of the people matter more than theological correctness. A king who provided equality, prosperity, and peace—even if he was an asura—deserves to be honoured. Onam is Kerala's annual reaffirmation of this value system. The ten-day celebration builds to a collective experience of what that Golden Age felt like: the Pookalam (flower carpet) at the threshold is a welcome mat for a beloved guest; the Sadya (26-dish feast on a banana leaf) is the feast of abundance that Mahabali provided; the Vallam Kali (snake boat race) with its crews of over 100 rowers moving in perfect synchrony is a demonstration of what collective effort can achieve. Onam is simultaneously a festival of grief (for a king who was taken), gratitude (for his annual return), and aspiration (for the society he represented).",
      "RegionalRituals": {
        "South": "The celebration includes 'Pookalam' (flower carpets), 'Vallam Kali' (snake boat races), and the 'Onasadya' feast served on banana leaves. Onam is observed across Kerala's five regions—Malabar in the north, Central Kerala, and Travancore in the south—with variations that reflect local tradition. The Pookalam (flower carpet) competition is the festival's most visible art form: concentric rings of fresh flowers, laid daily on the ground outside the home, beginning small on the first day (Atham) and expanding to an elaborate, large-format design by Thiruvonam (the tenth and main day). The flowers must be fresh and the design must be created within a single morning. The Onam Sadya—the ceremonial feast served on a banana leaf—is the most elaborate meal in Kerala's culinary tradition: up to 26 dishes served in a specific sequence and spatial arrangement on the leaf, beginning with papadum and Sarkara Varatti (candied banana chips) and ending with two types of payasam. The Vallam Kali (snake boat race) at Aranmula and Alappuzha, with 100-oarsmen boats moving in perfect synchrony to the 'Vanchipattu' (boat song), is Kerala's most dramatic sporting-cultural event."
