    {
      "Name": "Pongal",
      "Regions": ["South"],
      "History": "Pongal is Tamil Nadu's most important festival—a four-day harvest celebration of extraordinary antiquity, with literary references in Sangam poetry dating back over 2,000 years. The word 'Pongal' means 'to boil over' in Tamil, and the central ritual is the boiling of freshly harvested rice with milk and jaggery in a clay pot in the open air under the sun, allowed to overflow—symbolising abundance overflowing its boundaries. The four days each have a specific purpose: Bhogi Pongal marks the burning of old possessions and the clearing of the past; Surya Pongal is the main day of offering to the Sun God; Mattu Pongal honours cattle, who are decorated with flowers, painted horns, and garlands; Kaanum Pongal is a day for family visits and reunions. Unlike most Hindu festivals that draw from Sanskritic or Puranic traditions, Pongal is rooted in the ancient Dravidian agrarian tradition—a direct thanksgiving to the sun, rain, and cattle that made the harvest possible, predating the overlay of Brahminic ritual.",
      "Significance": "Pongal's significance lies in its directness and its antiquity. It does not require a priest, a temple, or a scripture. Its central ritual—boiling rice in an open clay pot in the morning sun until it overflows—is performed in the courtyard, in the open air, by the family together, with the sun as the direct witness. The overflow is intentional and celebrated: 'Pongalo Pongal!'—the shout that greets the moment the milk boils over—is an affirmation that abundance cannot be contained, that good fortune spills outward and blesses everything around it. Mattu Pongal—the day devoted to cattle—carries a significance that the modern world has largely lost: the acknowledgement that the animals who work alongside humans to produce food deserve recognition, rest, and celebration. In an agrarian civilisation, the bull and the cow were not merely useful animals; they were partners in survival. The decorated horns, the garlands, the kolams drawn around them—these are not sentiment but debt acknowledgement. Pongal is the annual reminder that human prosperity is never solely a human achievement; it rests on the labour of the earth, the water, the sun, and the animals who give themselves to the work.",
      "RegionalRituals": {
        "South": "Pongal's four-day sequence each has a completely distinct character. Bhogi Pongal (Day 1) begins before dawn with bonfires of old possessions—worn clothes, broken furniture, old mats—a physical clearing of the past year. In Andhra Pradesh and Telangana, children roll in front of the bonfire in a ritual called 'Bhogi Pallu,' having raw gooseberries, flower petals, and coins poured over their heads. Surya Pongal (Day 2) is the main event: the clay pot of rice and milk is placed in the sun-facing direction of the courtyard, the sun is invoked, and the moment the milk boils over, the family shouts 'Pongalo Pongal!' together. Mattu Pongal (Day 3) belongs to cattle: bulls and cows are bathed, their horns painted in bright colours, decorated with garlands and tinkling bells, and offered pongal. 'Jallikattu'—the bull-taming sport of Tamil Nadu, observed near Madurai and Tiruchirappalli—is legally conducted on this day, despite periodic controversy. Kaanum Pongal (Day 4) is for family visits and public recreation, with rivers, parks, and beaches crowded with families."
