    {
      "Name": "Bihu",
      "Regions": ["East"],
      "History": "Bihu is the soul festival of Assam—not one but three distinct celebrations marking the three turning points of the agrarian year: Rongali Bihu (April), the spring festival of planting; Kongali Bihu (October), the festival of the depleted harvest, marked by quiet prayer rather than celebration; and Bhogali Bihu (January), the festival of the completed harvest and communal feasting. The word 'Bihu' is believed to derive from the Sanskrit 'Vishuvat'—the equinox. Rongali Bihu is the most exuberant: young men and women dress in traditional mekhela chador and dhoti, and perform the Bihu dance together—a dance of extraordinary energy characterised by rapid hip movements and arched backs that is unique in Indian classical and folk traditions. The Bihu dance was not always public—it began as a fertility ritual of the fields, performed between young unmarried men and women as a form of courtship. Over centuries, it has evolved into Assam's defining cultural expression, recognised by UNESCO as an Intangible Cultural Heritage in 2023.",
      "Significance": "Bihu's significance is threefold—ecological, social, and existential—and each of the three Bihus carries a different emotional register. Rongali Bihu (spring) is pure joy: the earth is new, the paddy is planted, the young have danced all night. Kongali Bihu (autumn) is contemplative—the granaries are not yet full, the harvest is uncertain, and the festival is marked by quiet lamp-lighting rather than exuberance. Bhogali Bihu (winter) is celebration and relief—the harvest is done, the granaries overflow, and the community eats together in the meji (communal bonfire). This three-part structure makes Bihu unique among Indian festivals: it does not pretend that the year is uniformly joyful. It has a festival for the lean season, acknowledging that the cycle of scarcity is as real as the cycle of abundance. The Bihu dance's social significance is equally important: it is one of the very few traditional Indian folk dances that has always been performed by both men and women together, in courtship, with full social approval. The dance is an expression of the vitality of the community and the health of its intergenerational bond—the joy of being young, Assamese, and alive.",
      "RegionalRituals": {
        "East": "Assam's three Bihus each have a completely distinct emotional register and ritual structure. Rongali Bihu (April) is the spring planting festival and the most exuberant: young men and women in traditional attire—Mekhela Chador for women, Dhoti and Gamosa for men—perform the Bihu dance in open fields to the beat of the Dhol (drum) and Pepa (buffalo horn flute). The dance is performed in courtship pairs, and the Husori tradition—groups of young men visiting houses at dawn to perform Bihu songs and receive blessings—is the community's formal welcome of the season. Kongali Bihu (October) is the 'poor Bihu'—the granaries are not yet full and the harvest uncertain. Earth lamps are lit at the base of the Tulsi plant and the granary post in a quiet, reflective ritual that acknowledges the year's hardship without despair. Bhogali Bihu (January) is the harvest festival proper: community Meji bonfires are built from bamboo and thatch the day before, and on Bihu morning, the fire is lit and the community gathers for communal feasting on Til Pitha, Sunga Pitha, and Jolpan—exclusively rice-based foods."
