    {
      "Name": "Eid-ul-Adha",
      "Regions": ["North", "South", "East", "West", "Central"],
      "History": "Eid-ul-Adha—'the Festival of Sacrifice'—is the second and greater of the two canonical Islamic festivals, commemorating one of the most fundamental stories shared across Islam, Judaism, and Christianity: the test of faith of Prophet Ibrahim. Commanded by God in a dream to sacrifice his son Ismail, Ibrahim prepared to comply. As he raised the knife, God intervened and provided a ram as a substitute—a moment of divine mercy affirming that the intention of complete surrender to God is what is demanded, not the act itself. Muslims worldwide commemorate this by sacrificing a goat, sheep, cow, or camel, with the meat divided into three portions: one for the family, one for relatives and friends, and one for the poor—ensuring that no one in the community goes without food on the day of the festival. Eid-ul-Adha falls on the 10th of Dhul Hijjah, the last month of the Islamic calendar, coinciding with the Hajj pilgrimage in Mecca. In India, the festival has been observed since the arrival of Islam in the subcontinent, and the tradition of public sacrifice followed by communal feasting has been a cornerstone of Muslim community life for over a thousand years.",
      "Significance": "The significance of Eid-ul-Adha rests on the story's most difficult moment—not the sacrifice itself, but the dream. Ibrahim did not receive a direct command; he received a dream, which in Islamic theology is a lower form of revelation than direct speech. He chose to interpret it as a divine command and prepared to act. This is the theological core: the willingness to surrender the most precious thing you have—not because you are certain, but because you are faithful. The ram that replaced Ismail at the last moment is understood as divine confirmation that the intention of surrender was sufficient; the physical act was not required. This is why the Eid-ul-Adha sacrifice is described as an act of worship rather than an act of propitiation—you are not giving God something God needs; you are demonstrating the quality of your own surrender. The tripartite distribution of the sacrificed animal—one-third to family, one-third to friends and neighbours, one-third to the poor—is a practical enactment of the Islamic social contract: abundance is not for personal accumulation but for circulation. No one in the community should be without meat on this day. The festival is a simultaneous act of personal devotion and social responsibility.",
      "RegionalRituals": {
        "North": "In North India, Eid-ul-Adha begins at dawn with bathing, new clothes, and the Eid prayer at Eidgahs and mosques. The 'Qurbani' (animal sacrifice) follows the prayer—in urban areas, this is conducted in designated community sites rather than in streets, with the meat distributed in three portions: one for family, one for neighbours and friends, and one for the poor. In Delhi, Lucknow, and Agra, the day is marked by extraordinary cooking: Mutton Dum Biryani, Nihari (slow-cooked shank), Korma, and Sheer Khurma are prepared in quantities that feed extended families and neighbours across the day. Lucknow's Eid-ul-Adha retains the Nawabi tradition of gifting—particularly the gifting of traditional embroidered 'sherwani' cloth to family members.",
        "South": "In Hyderabad—whose old city retains one of India's most intact Muslim cultural traditions—Eid-ul-Adha is the year's most significant food event. Hyderabadi Mutton Dum Biryani, cooked with the 'dum' (sealed vessel) method and specific proportions of basmati rice, saffron, fried onions, and spice mix unique to the city, is prepared in enormous quantities from before dawn. The Qurbani meat distribution in Hyderabad's old city follows a meticulous system, with community leaders ensuring distribution reaches the poorest families first. In Kerala's Malabar region, the Eid feast includes the distinctive 'Malabar Mutton Biryani' and 'Pathiri'—rice flour flatbread—alongside traditional sweetmeats.",
        "West": "In Mumbai, the Eid-ul-Adha celebration centres on Mohammad Ali Road and the Bhendi Bazaar area, where community kitchens operate through the night before and the morning of Eid, producing Biryani, Haleem, and Kebabs at industrial scale for distribution to the poor and for sale. The Qurbani in Mumbai's Muslim-concentrated areas is organised by local Jamaat committees who manage the logistics of animal procurement, sacrifice, and distribution. The day is marked by intense cross-community interaction—Hindu and Christian neighbours visiting Muslim households for Eid greetings and sharing in the feast.",
        "East": "In Kolkata's Metiabruz and Park Circus areas—which have significant Muslim populations with cultural connections to Nawabi Lucknow—Eid-ul-Adha is observed with both solemnity and festivity. 'Shahi Tukda'—deep-fried bread soaked in sweet milk and rose water, a Nawabi dessert—is the Eid dessert of Kolkata's Muslim tradition. The Qurbani of a full cow (Bakra Eid's name comes from 'bakra'—goat—though cows are also sacrificed where legally permitted) is conducted with care for community sensitivities in a city of mixed religions.",
        "Central": "Marked by solemn prayers followed by joyful family reunions and the distribution of meat to tribal and rural communities to ensure everyone participates in the feast. In Bhopal and the major cities of MP and Chhattisgarh, Eid-ul-Adha fuses Nawabi Hyderabadi and North Indian culinary traditions. The 'Bhopali Gosht Korma'—a slow-cooked mutton preparation in a gravy base unique to Bhopal—is the centrepiece of the Eid feast, accompanied by 'Bhopali Puri' and rice. In rural and tribal areas of Central India with Muslim communities, the Eid feast is a genuinely communal event that includes tribal and Hindu neighbours—a tradition of mutual hospitality that reflects the composite rural culture of the region."
      },
