    {
      "Name": "Navroz",
      "Regions": ["West", "Central", "North"],
      "History": "Navroz—'New Day' in Persian—is the ancient Persian New Year marking the Spring Equinox, when the sun crosses the celestial equator and day and night are of equal length. Its origins are traced to the legendary Persian King Jamshed of the Pishdadian dynasty, who is said to have established Navroz over 3,000 years ago. Zoroaster—the prophet of Zoroastrianism, the world's first monotheistic religion—incorporated Navroz into Zoroastrian practice as a festival of renewal, fire, and the victory of light over darkness. When the Zoroastrians fled Persian persecution after the Arab conquest of Persia in the 7th century CE, a group sailed to India and landed on the coast of Gujarat. The Indian Zoroastrians became the Parsi community—'Parsi' meaning Persian—and brought Navroz with them. The Parsi community of India is one of the smallest religious minorities in the world (under 70,000 today) yet has produced figures of extraordinary national and global importance—including Jamshedji Tata, Homi Bhabha, Zubin Mehta, and Freddie Mercury. Their Navroz celebration features the Haft-Seen table: seven items beginning with the Persian letter 'S,' each symbolising an aspect of renewal.",
      "Significance": "The significance of Navroz as observed by the Parsi community of India is inseparable from the extraordinary story of the community itself—a community that chose cultural preservation over assimilation and spiritual integrity over physical safety, and has maintained both for 1,300 years in a country that was not their origin. The Haft-Seen table—seven items beginning with the Persian letter 'S'—encodes Zoroastrian cosmology in domestic objects: Sabzeh (sprouted wheat, representing rebirth), Samanu (wheat pudding, representing affluence), Senjed (dried lotus fruit, representing love), Sir (garlic, representing medicine), Sib (apple, representing health and beauty), Somaq (sumac, representing the colour of sunrise), and Serkeh (vinegar, representing age and patience). Together, they are a complete map of a good life. The central element of Zoroastrian theology—the cosmic struggle between Ahura Mazda (Wise Lord, the force of good) and Angra Mainyu (the force of evil), with humans as the conscious participants who choose which side to strengthen—gives Navroz its moral urgency. The renewal of the year at the spring equinox is not merely seasonal; it is a renewal of the individual's commitment to Good Thoughts, Good Words, and Good Deeds.",
      "RegionalRituals": {
        "West": "In Mumbai and Gujarat—home to over 60% of India's Parsi population—Navroz is the most significant event in the Parsi community calendar. The day begins before dawn with prayers at the Agiari (fire temple), where the sacred fire, maintained continuously for centuries, is offered sandalwood at the specific Navroz auspicious hour. Homes are cleaned and decorated with chalk designs ('Rangoli') on the threshold and fresh flowers throughout. The Haft-Seen table—the seven items beginning with 'S'—is arranged with prayer verses. The community gathers for 'Jashn' (thanksgiving ceremony) at the Agiari. The traditional Parsi breakfast of 'Sev' (sweet vermicelli) and 'Dahi' (yogurt) is served, and the day is spent in family visits.",
        "Central": "In Surat (Gujarat) and smaller Parsi communities in Central India, Navroz is observed with the intimacy of a small, tightly knit religious minority that has maintained its traditions with extraordinary fidelity. The fire temples of Surat—some of the oldest in India, housing fires that have not been extinguished for centuries—receive their highest footfall of the year on Navroz. The Parsi community's contribution to Surat's commercial and philanthropic culture—from the Tata family (Navsari origin) to generations of cotton and shipping merchants—is acknowledged on Navroz through community charitable activities.",
        "North": "Though a small community, Parsis in Delhi host cultural events and invite friends of all faiths to share traditional Iranian delicacies. In Delhi, the small but culturally distinctive Parsi community—with institutions like the Zoroastrian Trust Funds and the Rustom Faramna Agiari (fire temple)—observes Navroz with visits to the fire temple for prayers, the preparation of the Haft-Seen table at home, and community gatherings that feature traditional Persian and Parsi cuisine: Boi Fish in white sauce, Lagan nu Custard, Sali Boti, and Dhansak (the Parsi signature dish of lentils and meat). The community's 'Navroz Milan' events in Delhi draw participation from non-Parsi guests, making the festival a moment of cultural education as well as celebration."
      },
