    {
      "Name": "Guru Gobind Singh Jayanti",
      "Regions": ["North", "South", "East", "West", "Central"],
      "History": "Guru Gobind Singh Jayanti marks the birth of the 10th and final human Guru of Sikhism, born Gobind Rai on December 22, 1666, in Patna Sahib, Bihar. His life is one of the most extraordinary in the history of any religion: his father, Guru Tegh Bahadur, was publicly executed in Delhi by Aurangzeb for refusing to convert to Islam—the first recorded execution in history of a religious leader for defending the rights of another religion (the Kashmiri Pandits). The young Gobind Rai assumed the Guruship at age nine. In 1699, he created the Khalsa Panth and transformed his own name to Gobind Singh. He lost all four of his sons to Mughal persecution—his two elder sons in battle, his two younger sons bricked alive in a wall in Sirhind on Aurangzeb's orders—yet he composed the Zafarnama (Letter of Victory) to Aurangzeb from exile, a document of such moral force that it is studied as philosophy. His final act was to declare the Guru Granth Sahib—the scripture—as the eternal living Guru, ending the line of human Gurus. He died in 1708 in Nanded, Maharashtra, from wounds inflicted by an assassin—but the Khalsa he created had already become unstoppable.",
      "Significance": "The significance of Guru Gobind Singh Jayanti lies in the model of the Guru himself—a figure who held poetry and the sword with equal mastery, who composed devotional hymns in the morning and organised cavalry charges in the afternoon, and who never asked his followers to give what he himself was not prepared to give. He gave his four sons and his own life to the cause he built. His creation of the Khalsa was a declaration that spiritual life and political resistance are not in contradiction—that the obligation to protect the weak is as much a religious duty as prayer. His letter to Aurangzeb, the Zafarnama, written in Persian from exile after he had lost his entire family, is one of the most extraordinary documents in the history of religious literature: a letter that refuses grief, refuses defeat, and holds the emperor morally accountable with complete equanimity. His final instruction—to regard the Guru Granth Sahib as the living Guru—was an act of institutional genius: by making the scripture itself the permanent Guru, he protected the Sikh community from the vulnerability of human succession, from the corruption of living authority, and from the personality cults that have destroyed so many religious movements.",
      "RegionalRituals": {
        "North": "The primary celebration is at Takht Sri Patna Sahib in Bihar (the birthplace) and at the Golden Temple in Amritsar, but across North India—particularly Punjab, Haryana, Delhi, and UP—the Jayanti is marked by Akhand Paths, Nagar Kirtans, and the massive community kitchens (Langar) that feed thousands. In Anandpur Sahib—where the Guru founded the Khalsa in 1699—the Jayanti Nagar Kirtan is the second most significant annual event after Hola Mohalla. In Delhi, the Rakabganj Gurudwara—built on the site where Guru Tegh Bahadur's headless body was cremated after his execution by Aurangzeb—is a particularly emotionally charged site for the Guru Gobind Singh Jayanti observance.",
        "South": "In Nanded, Maharashtra—where Guru Gobind Singh spent his final years and was fatally wounded in 1708—the Takht Sachkhand Shri Hazur Sahib is one of the five Takhts (seats of temporal authority) of Sikhism and the second-most sacred site for the Jayanti after Patna Sahib. Hazur Sahib sits on the bank of the Godavari river, and the Jayanti here draws pilgrims from across Maharashtra, Karnataka, and Andhra Pradesh—a significant event that has made Nanded one of the most important Sikh pilgrimage centres in South India.",
        "West": "In Mumbai and Pune, the Sikh community commemorates the Guru with Nagar Kirtans that move through the city accompanied by Gatka demonstrations and kirtan teams. In Maharashtra specifically, the Guru Gobind Singh Jayanti has additional significance: the Guru's 'Zafarnama'—his letter to Aurangzeb—is studied as a document of moral courage, and its themes of standing against injustice resonate with Maharashtra's own tradition of resistance through Shivaji and the Maratha movement. Several Maharashtra Gurudwaras hold historical lectures on the Jayanti.",
        "East": "Patna Sahib—the Takht Sri Harmandir Ji in Patna, Bihar—is the birthplace of Guru Gobind Singh and the holiest site for the Jayanti observance. The Gurudwara sits in the old Patna city area near the Ganges, and the Jayanti draws pilgrims from across Bihar, Jharkhand, Bengal, and Uttar Pradesh. The Patna Sahib Langar on Jayanti day is one of the largest community meals in Bihar, served to hundreds of thousands of pilgrims regardless of faith. The ceremony of 'Sukhasan'—the Guru Granth Sahib being ceremonially carried to its night resting place—at Patna Sahib on Jayanti evening is one of the most moving rituals in Sikh practice.",
        "Central": "Gurudwaras in Gwalior and Indore host continuous reading of the scriptures and serve traditional meals to thousands of devotees. In Gwalior—historically connected to the Sikh tradition through the Gwalior Fort, where Guru Hargobind Singh (the 6th Guru) was imprisoned by Mughal Emperor Jahangir—the Jayanti carries a historical dimension alongside the devotional. The Gurudwara Data Bandi Chhor at Gwalior Fort (commemorating the Guru's release along with 52 princes, an event celebrated as Bandi Chhor Divas on Diwali) is one of the historically significant Sikh sites in Central India."
      },
