    {
      "Name": "Vaikunta Ekadashi",
      "Regions": ["South", "Central", "North"],
      "History": "Vaikunta Ekadashi is the most sacred of the 24 Ekadashis (11th days of the lunar fortnight) in the Vaishnava calendar, falling in the month of Dhanurmasa (December-January). Its origin is recorded in the Padma Purana: the demon Muran had obtained a boon making him invincible against all weapons. Vishnu fought him for a thousand years without success and retreated into a cave to sleep. From his exhausted body emerged a divine feminine form—Ekadashi—who slew Muran with a single look. In gratitude, Vishnu declared that those who fast on this day would receive the same merit as performing all 10,000 yagnas, and that the gates of Vaikunta (Vishnu's celestial abode) would remain open for them. At the famous Srirangam Ranganathaswamy Temple in Tamil Nadu, a special gateway called 'Paramapada Vasal' (the Gate of Heaven) is opened only on this day. Devotees believe that passing through it grants liberation. Lakhs of pilgrims arrive before dawn to be among the first through the gate. The Tirupati Balaji Temple sees its largest single-day footfall of the year on Vaikunta Ekadashi—often over 100,000 pilgrims.",
      "Significance": "Vaikunta Ekadashi's significance rests on the Vaishnava theology of liberation—the belief that the ultimate purpose of human life is to escape the cycle of birth and death and enter the eternal presence of Vishnu in Vaikunta. The Paramapada Vasal—Gate of Heaven—opened only on this day at the Srirangam and Tirupati temples is a physical enactment of a theological promise: the gate to liberation is not permanently closed; there are moments in cosmic time when it swings open, and the sincere seeker who arrives at the right moment can pass through. The practice of fasting on all 24 Ekadashis—the 11th days of the lunar fortnight—is itself a complete spiritual discipline in the Vaishnava tradition: fasting from grain and legumes, the foods most connected to the earth cycle, and spending the day in prayer and scripture reading. Vaikunta Ekadashi is the culmination of this year-long practice—the Ekadashi when the merit is greatest and the liberation closest. Its significance for the ordinary devotee is also immediate: it is the one night when the temple stays open through the night, when the community gathers and maintains collective vigil, and when the individual's private spiritual aspiration becomes a shared, public act.",
      "RegionalRituals": {
        "South": "In Tamil Nadu—at the Srirangam Ranganathaswamy Temple (the largest functioning Hindu temple in the world by area) and at Tirupati Balaji—Vaikunta Ekadashi is the most attended single day in the temple calendar. At Srirangam, the 'Paramapada Vasal' (Gate of Heaven) is opened only on this night: devotees queue for hours to be among the first to pass through the gateway, which opens at midnight. The crowd at Tirupati on Vaikunta Ekadashi—regularly exceeding 100,000 in a single day—tests even Tirupati's extraordinary visitor management capacity. In Kerala, the Vaikunta Ekadashi at Guruvayur Temple draws a similar concentration of pilgrims.",
        "North": "In North India, Vaikunta Ekadashi is observed as a day of strict fasting from grains and legumes, extended prayer, and reading of the Bhagavad Gita. The Dwadashi (12th day) morning is the fast-breaking day, when devotees eat 'Ekadashi Upavas'—foods specifically permitted during the fast, including fruits, milk, sabudana, and buckwheat. The Mathura-Vrindavan region, as the geographical heartland of Vaishnava devotion, observes the day with overnight vigils at the major Krishna temples. Vrindavan's 5,000+ temples keep their sanctuaries open through the night, and the town's lights and music continue until dawn.",
        "Central": "In Maharashtra and the Warkari tradition of Vaishnava devotion, Ekadashi is the most important regular observance in the devotional calendar—the Warkari pilgrims observe every Ekadashi as a mini-pilgrimage, with the Vaikunta Ekadashi being the culminating one. Pandharpur Wari (pilgrimage to Pandharpur) has specific Ekadashi dimensions, with the Vitthal (Vithoba) temple at Pandharpur—the centre of the Warkari tradition—observing Vaikunta Ekadashi with its largest annual ritual sequence. The night-long vigil at Pandharpur's Vitthal Temple, with thousands of Warkaris singing 'abhanga' (devotional compositions by saint-poets like Tukaram and Dnyaneshwar), is one of the most sustained acts of collective devotion in Maharashtra."
      },
