    {
      "Name": "Bathukamma",
      "Regions": ["South", "Central"],
      "History": "Bathukamma is a floral festival unique to the Telangana region of South India, celebrated during the nine days of Dasara in the months of Bhadrapada and Ashwija. The word 'Bathukamma' means 'Mother, come alive'—and the festival is addressed directly to Goddess Gauri (a form of Parvati), inviting her to awaken after a celestial battle. According to the legend, after Gauri defeated the demon Mahishasura, she was so exhausted that she fell into a deep sleep. Her devotees—the women of Telangana—woke her with the beauty of flowers. Every day of Bathukamma, women collect and arrange medicinal and aromatic wildflowers—Tangedi (senna), Gunuka (cock's comb), Banti (chrysanthemum), and others—in concentric layers in a conical form on a brass plate, creating a living tower of colour. The flowers used are not merely decorative: many have medicinal properties and their use during the rainy season is believed to purify local water bodies and reduce malaria. Women gather in groups, place their Bathukammas in a circle, sing the Bathukamma songs, dance around them, and finally immerse them in a lake or river—returning the flowers to the earth.",
      "Significance": "Bathukamma's significance lies in what it chooses as its medium: flowers, not stone; circles, not hierarchies; singing, not scripture. The festival belongs entirely to the women of Telangana—they collect the flowers, arrange them, carry them, dance around them, and immerse them. There are no priests, no temples, no male intermediaries. The Goddess is addressed directly, informally, with songs composed in Telugu that speak to her as a mother being woken from sleep. This directness is the festival's theological core: Gauri is not distant, not requiring elaborate ritual preparation, not accessible only through specialist knowledge. She is a mother who can be called awake by women who love her. The flowers used are not chosen for beauty alone—many are medicinal plants that flower during the monsoon season and whose immersion in water bodies is believed to have purifying properties. The ecological dimension of Bathukamma is not accidental: the festival encodes traditional environmental knowledge about which plants, introduced to still water at which time of year, reduce waterborne disease. The Bathukamma songs—composed in the oral tradition—are a form of women's literature that has survived entirely outside the written record, transmitted from mother to daughter across generations.",
      "RegionalRituals": {
        "South": "Bathukamma is observed over nine days in Telangana (and parts of Andhra Pradesh), with a different type of flower arrangement and a different song on each day. The flower towers are built in a specific structure: a brass plate base, with flowers arranged in concentric rings of alternating types, each ring of a different colour, rising to a pointed crown at the top. The flowers are collected from fields and roadsides each morning—specifically the Tangedu (Senna), Banti (Chrysanthemum), Gunuka (cock's comb), and Seethaphal (custard apple flower) that bloom in the Telangana landscape during the Bhadrapada-Ashwija period. The Bathukamma songs—composed in Telugu, sung in call-and-response format by groups of women dancing in a circle around the flower towers—are a form of women's devotional literature unique to Telangana. The immersion of the Bathukamma in a local lake or pond on Saddula Bathukamma (the ninth and final day) is both a release and a renewal—the flowers return to the water that nourished them, and the women return home to begin the Dasara preparations.",
        "Central": "In the border regions of Maharashtra and Chhattisgarh, Telugu-speaking communities celebrate with floral arrangements and folk singing. In the border districts of Chhattisgarh and Maharashtra that share cultural connections with Telangana—particularly in areas with Telugu-speaking communities—Bathukamma is observed in its authentic Telangana form, with the full nine-day flower arrangement tradition. These communities maintain the festival as a marker of cultural identity and community cohesion in a region where they live among speakers of Marathi and Hindi. The Chhattisgarh government has in recent years included Bathukamma in its list of state-recognised festivals in recognition of the Telugu-speaking population."
      },
