    {
      "Name": "Raja Parba",
      "Regions": ["East"],
      "History": "Raja Parba—'the festival of the queen'—is a unique three-day festival of Odisha celebrating Bhudevi, the Earth Goddess, and the onset of the monsoon. It falls in the month of Ashadha (mid-June), precisely when the monsoon arrives in Odisha, and the festival's core belief is that the Earth is menstruating during these three days—entering a period of fertile rest before the agricultural year begins. For three days, the earth is worshipped rather than worked: no plowing, no digging, no cultivation. The earth is given her rest, as women are given theirs. Young women and girls are central to the festival—they rest from housework, eat special foods (poda pitha—baked cakes), swing on rope swings hung from trees, play games, and enjoy a rare three-day holiday from domestic labor. The festival is explicitly a celebration of womanhood and fertility—both the earth's and women's. Raja Parba predates any Brahminic religious overlay and belongs to the ancient agrarian traditions of Odisha's tribal communities, in which the earth is female, the rain is male, and the monsoon's arrival is a cosmic union that must be honored with celebration and rest.",
      "Significance": "Raja Parba's significance is unique in the Indian festival calendar: it is the only major festival that explicitly celebrates the earth's menstruation as a sacred event—and by extension, treats the menstrual cycle of women as something equally sacred rather than polluting. In most Hindu traditions, menstruation is a period of ritual restriction; in Raja Parba, it is the central theological event of the festival. The earth is menstruating, therefore the earth is fertile; she is entering her reproductive phase, therefore she must be honoured and rested. The festival's three-day suspension of all agricultural work—no plowing, no digging, no cutting—is a rest given to the earth as an equal: the same consideration given to a woman in her rest period. The celebration of young women and girls during Raja Parba—their freedom from housework, their feasting, their games, their swings—extends this logic: if the earth's fertility is sacred, so is the woman's. Raja Parba belongs to the pre-Brahminic tribal traditions of Odisha, and its survival into the present is a remarkable preservation of a world-view in which the feminine cycle is the primary cosmic rhythm—not a secondary, private matter but the very foundation of agricultural life and therefore of civilisation.",
      "RegionalRituals": {
        "East": "Raja Parba is Odisha's most distinctive regional festival—observed over three days in the month of Ashadha (mid-June) when the earth is understood to be in her menstrual period. The festival begins on 'Pahili Raja' (First Day), when the earth's menstrual cycle is believed to begin, and continues through 'Raja' (Main Day) and 'Bhu Daha' (Earth Day). During these three days, no agricultural work is performed—no plowing, digging, or cutting—as the earth is in her sacred rest period. Young women and unmarried girls are the festival's central figures: they wear new clothes, apply Alta (red dye) to their feet, put flowers in their hair, and play on 'Raja Doli'—rope swings decorated with flowers and hung from large trees. The swings are not merely recreational but ritual: the back-and-forth motion is connected to the earth's fertility cycle. 'Poda Pitha'—a slow-baked (traditionally buried-in-embers) rice cake made with jaggery and coconut, wrapped in banana leaves—is the specific Raja Parba food, prepared in every home and shared with neighbours. The festival is simultaneously an agricultural rest period, a celebration of female fertility, and a rare institutional holiday for women from domestic labour."
