    {
      "Name": "Karthigai Deepam",
      "Regions": ["South"],
      "History": "Karthigai Deepam is one of the most ancient festivals in the Tamil calendar, celebrated in the Tamil month of Karthigai (November-December) when the Pleiades star cluster (Karthigai) reaches its highest point in the night sky. The festival's central myth is the resolution of the cosmic dispute between Brahma and Vishnu—each claiming supremacy. Shiva appeared between them as an infinite, beginningless pillar of fire (Jyotirlinga): Brahma took the form of a swan and flew upward to find its crown; Vishnu became a boar and burrowed downward to find its base. Neither could reach the end. Brahma lied that he had found the crown; Vishnu admitted defeat. Shiva condemned Brahma's falsehood, declaring he would never be worshipped as a primary deity. Karthigai Deepam commemorates the day this column of infinite fire appeared. At the Arunachaleswarar Temple in Tiruvannamalai, Tamil Nadu, the festival reaches its most dramatic expression: on the full moon night, a fire is lit on the summit of the Arunachala hill—the hill itself considered the manifestation of Shiva's fiery column—visible for miles in every direction. The act of lighting a lamp is the festival's central metaphor: every lamp lit at Karthigai is understood as a participation in the original divine light.",
      "Significance": "Karthigai Deepam's significance is rooted in the Tamil philosophical tradition's understanding of light as the fundamental metaphor for consciousness—and the lamp as the act of making consciousness visible. The festival's central theological story—Shiva appearing as an infinite column of fire to resolve a dispute between Brahma and Vishnu—encodes a specific teaching: neither the highest (the sky, Brahma's direction) nor the deepest (the earth, Vishnu's direction) contains the source of consciousness. It is infinite, beginningless, and without boundary. The lamp lit at Karthigai is a human participation in this infinite light—a small, finite flame that nonetheless shares the nature of the infinite fire. In the Tamil Shaiva tradition, this teaching is the foundation of the entire devotional path: the jyoti (flame) of the self, when purified through devotion, merges with the Jyoti (cosmic fire) of Shiva. The Tiruvannamalai Karthigai Deepam—the fire lit on the summit of Arunachala hill—is the most dramatic annual expression of this theology: the hill itself is the Jyotirlinga, and the fire on its summit is visible for 30 kilometres in every direction. The entire town below sits in darkness after sunset, and then the summit flames: consciousness revealing itself from above, while the community of devotees illuminates from below.",
      "RegionalRituals": {
        "South": "Karthigai Deepam is observed across Tamil Nadu with extraordinary intensity, but its most dramatic expression is at Tiruvannamalai—the site of the Arunachaleswarar Temple and the Arunachala hill, believed to be a manifestation of Shiva's column of infinite fire (Jyotirlinga). On the full moon night of Karthigai, a massive fire ('Mahadeepam') is lit on the summit of the 2,668-foot Arunachala hill, visible for approximately 30 kilometres in all directions. The lighting of the Mahadeepam—performed by the temple's priestly lineage using a specific pot of clarified butter and a flame carried from the temple sanctum—is the ritual culmination of days of preparation. Below the hill, the entire town of Tiruvannamalai celebrates with homes lit by rows of oil lamps ('Agal Vilakku'), streets illuminated, and hundreds of thousands of devotees performing the Girivalam—the barefoot circumambulation of the Arunachala hill (14 km)—through the night. In homes across Tamil Nadu, the day begins with the ritual of lighting the largest possible lamp at the doorway and progressively lighting smaller lamps to fill the entire house—an act of filling life with light from the threshold inward. The Karthigai Deepam lamp at Tiruvannamalai has been lit without interruption for over a thousand years."
