    {
      "Name": "Ambubachi Mela",
      "Regions": ["East"],
      "History": "The Ambubachi Mela is held annually at the Kamakhya Temple in Guwahati, Assam—one of the most powerful Shakti Peethas in India—in the month of Ashadha (June), and is the only festival in the Hindu tradition that explicitly celebrates the menstruation cycle of the Goddess. The Kamakhya Temple is built over a natural rock cleft believed to be the yoni (womb) of Goddess Sati—the mythological origin of all Shakti Peethas. According to the Devi Bhagavata Purana, Sati's body was dismembered by Vishnu's Sudarshana Chakra as Shiva carried her in grief across the universe; her yoni fell at Kamakhya. For three days during the Ambubachi period, the temple is closed: the Goddess is believed to be menstruating and in rest. A natural spring within the temple is said to run red during these days. On the fourth day, the temple reopens, and the cloth placed over the yoni pitha—now believed to be dyed red by the Goddess—is distributed as the most sacred prasad in the Tantric tradition. Thousands of Tantric practitioners, Aghoris, sadhus, and Shakta devotees from across South Asia gather for this festival, making it the largest annual assembly of Tantric practitioners in the world.",
      "Significance": "The significance of the Ambubachi Mela is its refusal of the universal taboo. In virtually every culture, menstruation has been treated as polluting, as a subject of silence, as a matter requiring restriction and concealment. Ambubachi inverts this completely: the menstruation of the Goddess is the most sacred event of the year at Kamakhya, and it is celebrated with the largest gathering of Tantric practitioners on earth. The theological significance is precise: the Goddess's menstruation is the signal of her fertility—the most powerful creative force in the universe is at its most potent. The three-day temple closure is not a restriction but a period of reverence: the Goddess is in a state of sacred power that requires stillness and respect. The red-stained cloth that is distributed as prasad on the fourth day is understood as the most potent blessing in the Tantric tradition—not because of what it physically is, but because of what it represents: the creative power of the Goddess made tangible. The festival's second significance is its challenge to Hindu normativity: Kamakhya is a Shakta Peetha operating entirely outside Brahminic Vaishnava traditions, and the Ambubachi Mela is its annual assertion that the feminine creative principle—in its most direct, physical form—is not the opposite of the sacred but its source.",
      "RegionalRituals": {
        "East": "The temple closes for three days while the Earth 'rests.' Upon reopening, devotees receive 'Raktabastra' (red cloth) as a highly auspicious blessing. The Ambubachi Mela at the Kamakhya Temple in Guwahati, Assam, is held annually during the three days of the Hindu month of Ashadha when the Brahmaputra river is believed to turn red—a natural phenomenon caused by soil mineral content during the monsoon—interpreted as the menstruation of the Earth Goddess. The Kamakhya Temple is built on the Nilachal Hill overlooking the Brahmaputra and is one of the 51 Shakti Peethas of India—the site where the yoni of Goddess Sati fell when her body was dismembered by Vishnu's Sudarshana Chakra. The three days of Ambubachi are among the most sacred in the Tantric calendar: the temple closes on the first day (Ambubachi start) and remains closed for three days, during which no puja is performed—the Goddess is in her menstrual rest. On the fourth day (Nivritti), the temple reopens to an extraordinary gathering. Tens of thousands of Tantric practitioners, Aghoris (ascetics of the cremation ground tradition), Vaishnava saints, sadhus of every Indian tradition, and lay devotees have assembled in the surrounding areas during the three closed days. The Nivritti morning sees the most intense human gathering on the Nilachal Hill—the sacred 'Raktabastra' (cloth believed to have absorbed the Goddess's menstrual discharge) is distributed as the most potent prasad in the Tantric tradition. The Ambubachi Mela is simultaneously the world's largest Tantric assembly, the most explicit celebration of the female creative principle in any living religious tradition, and one of the most emotionally overwhelming festival experiences in Northeast India."
